2–1451","1396–1460":"1396–1460","1405–1464":"1405–1464","–Male":"Overleden","1426":"1426","1455":"1455","1464":"1464"," 1460":"1460","1396":"1396","1451":"1451","1374":"1374","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1392":"1392","1405":"1405","Great Bealings, Suffolk, England":"Great Bealings, Suffolk, England","Kenton, Suffolk, England":"Kenton, Suffolk, England","Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England":"Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Byers Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1370–1464":"1370–1464","1374–1426":"1374–1426","1392–1451":"1392–1451","1396–1460":"1396–1460","1405–1464":"1405–1464","–Male":"Deceased","1426":"1426","1455":"1455","1464":"1464"," 1460":"1460","1396":"1396","1451":"1451","1374":"1374","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1392":"1392","1405":"1405","Great Bealings, Suffolk, England":"Great Bealings, Suffolk, England","Kenton, Suffolk, England":"Kenton, Suffolk, England","Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England":"Kettleburgh, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Byers Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ramsay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant (the usual spelling in Scotland) of   Ramsey  . The Scottish Ramsays derive from Simund <i>de Ramesie</i>, recorded before 1175, who went to Scotland from Ramsey (Huntingdonshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ramsey","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish (Antrim): habitational name from Ramsey (Huntingdonshire, now part of Cambridgeshire), from Old English <i>hramsa</i> ‘wild garlic’ + <i>ēg</i> ‘island, low-lying land’. Alternatively, the name may also arise from Ramsey (Essex), probably from the same etymology as the Huntingdonshire placename. However, this is unlikely to be the source of the Scottish surname. This form of the surname is also common in Ireland, where it is probably in most if not all cases an altered form of Scottish   Ramsay  ."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":85,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Ralph Ramsay Sheriff of Suffolk was born in 1370, in Kenton, Suffolk, England as the son of Ramsay. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Alice de Walsingham. He died in 1464, in his hometown, at